---
description: Prefer bold round price numbers over charm pricing
alwaysApply: true
---

# Pricing style: bold round numbers

When proposing or generating new prices, demo amounts, sample subscriptions,
docs, or fixture data: prefer whole / round currency values. They are easier
to digest at a glance and read better in tables, logs, and dashboards.

Avoid charm pricing (`.99`, `.95`, `.49`) unless the user explicitly asks for
it or a real-world product is being modelled.

```typescript
// BAD - charm pricing
unitAmount: 299   // €2.99
unitAmount: 1999  // €19.99
unitAmount: 995   // €9.95

// GOOD - bold round numbers
unitAmount: 300   // €3
unitAmount: 2000  // €20
unitAmount: 1000  // €10
```

Same rule applies to docs / READMEs / log messages:

```text
BAD:  €2.99 per view, €19.99/month, $9.99 trial
GOOD: €3 per view, €20/month, $10 trial
```

## Stripe-specific note

Stripe `Price` objects are immutable on `unit_amount`. Changing this constant
in code does not update an already-provisioned price. To migrate, either
deactivate the old price and rotate the `lookup_key`, or accept the divergence
for legacy environments.
